The '''National Association of Railroad Passengers''' ('''NARP''') "is the largest national membership advocacy organization for train and rail transit passengers" according to the association's website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.narprail.org/cms/index.php/main/contact |publisher=National Association of Railroad Passengers |title=NARP Contact Information |accessdate=2008-01-01 }}</ref>
== Early history == The organization was originally founded by [[Anthony Haswell (passenger rail advocate)|Anthony Haswell]] on May 18, 1967 to lobby for the continuation of [[passenger train]]s in the [[United States]]. Its lobbying efforts were hampered somewhat by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] political opposition to any sort of [[subsidy|subsidies]] to the privately owned railroads, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] political opposition to nationalization of the railroad industry. The proponents were aided by the fact that few in the federal government wanted to be held responsible for the seemingly inevitable extinction of the passenger train, which most regarded as tantamount to political suicide.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}
== Activities == NARP's small paid staff in Washington, D.C., spends most of its time educating members of Congress and their staffs about the value of passenger rail.
Each month, NARP publishes a monthly [[newsletter]] detailing news in the passenger rail world. It often includes stories about related [[legislation]] in Congress, Traveler's Advisories, and Travel Tips, with a particular focus on [[Amtrak]]. Paid circulation, corresponding to membership as of December 2007, was about 23,500.<ref>{{Cite news | last= | first= | author-link= | publication-date=2007-12 | date= | year=2007 | title=Statement of Ownership, Management, and Circulation | periodical=NARP News | series= | publication-place=Washington, DC, USA | place= | publisher=Ross Capon | volume=41 | issue=11 | pages=4 | url= | issn= | doi= | oclc= | accessdate=}}</ref>
NARP also conducts interviews with media on passenger rail related issues, and encourages its members to lobby their legislators for funding for Amtrak and other improvements to the rail [[infrastructure]]. The organization's website includes action alerts and news releases. Travel discounts are a member benefit.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/ContentServer?pagename=Amtrak/am2Copy/Simple_Copy_Page&c=am2Copy&cid=1083262194530 | title = NARP Membership Discount | accessdate = 2007-12-19 | author = | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = | year = | month = | work = | publisher = National Railroad Passenger Corporation | pages = | doi = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = }}</ref>
== Organization == NARP is divided into twelve membership regions for the purposes of electing members to the [[board of directors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.narprail.org/cms/index.php/resources/list/C36/ |publisher=National Association of Railroad Passengers |title=Resources and Links |accessdate=2007-12-27 }}</ref> The various regions and their elected representatives usually meet annually. The regions are grouped into four districts, each of which elects a vice-president.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.narprail.org/cms/index.php/resources/more/regions/ |publisher=National Association of Railroad Passengers |title=Maps of Membership Regions & Vice Presidentsâ€™ Districts |accessdate=2007-12-27 }}</ref> In addition to the above, the members elect a president, a secretary, and a treasurer.
In addition to the elected leadership, there is a small paid staff in Washington, D.C., that includes an executive director, an assistant, a director of finance and administration, and an office manager.
As of May 2009, the president was Ross B. Capon and the chairman was George Chilson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.narprail.org/cms/index.php/resources/more/committee/ |publisher=http://www.narprail.org/cms/index.php/resources/more/officers/ |title=NARP Officers and Board of Directors |accessdate=2009-05-16 }}</ref>
